Exercise 1: Correlation

  1. In the KiGGS dataset, compute the Pearson and Spearman correlation coefficient for the two variables sys1 and sys2 and hypothesis tests whether the two variables are associated or not. Interpret the results, and decide which of the two coefficients you would report in your analysis and why.
sbp1 <- as.numeric(as.character(dat$sys1))
sbp2 <- as.numeric(as.character(dat$sys2))
hist(sbp1)

hist(sbp2)

plot(sbp1,sbp2)

res <- cor.test(sbp1, sbp2, use = "complete.obs", method = "pearson")
res #Pearson
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  sbp1 and sbp2
## t = 193.34, df = 14563, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.8436990 0.8528071
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.8483158
cor(sbp1, sbp2, use = "complete.obs", method = "spearman") #Spearman
## [1] 0.8405508

Conclusion: We can conclude that sys1 and sys2 are significantly correlated with a correlation coefficient of 0.84 and p-value of 2.2^{-16}. We will report the Pearson coefficient since both the variables are metric variables as well as they are normally distributed

Exercise 2: Linear regression

  1. Predict sys2 by sys1 using a simple linear regression, and interpret the results.
res1 <- lm(sbp2 ~ sbp1)
summary(res1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = sbp2 ~ sbp1)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -37.677  -3.869  -0.158   3.842  31.458 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 16.828706   0.465916   36.12   <2e-16 ***
## sbp1         0.826940   0.004277  193.34   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 6.305 on 14563 degrees of freedom
##   (3075 observations deleted due to missingness)
## Multiple R-squared:  0.7196, Adjusted R-squared:  0.7196 
## F-statistic: 3.738e+04 on 1 and 14563 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
head(predict(res1))
##         1         2         3         4         5         8 
## 101.17660 102.83049 106.96519 113.58071  98.69578  99.52272

Conclusion: Since the p-value is less than 0.05, we are confident that the coefficients i.e.0 and 1 are not zero, meaning the coefficients does in fact add value to the model by helping to explain the variance within our dependent variable and thus null hypothesis is rejected.

Exercise 3: Visualization of regression (optional)

Use the functions in ggplot2 to compute a scatter plot and insert the regression line of the analysis in exercise 2a.

library(tidyverse)
##  Attaching packages  tidyverse 1.3.2 
##  ggplot2 3.3.6       purrr   0.3.5 
##  tibble  3.1.8       dplyr   1.0.10
##  tidyr   1.2.1       stringr 1.4.1 
##  readr   2.1.3       forcats 0.5.2 
##  Conflicts  tidyverse_conflicts() 
##  dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
##  dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()
ggplot(data = dat, aes(x = sbp1, y = sbp2)) +
  geom_point(color = "grey") +
  geom_smooth(method='lm',color='black') +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x='sbp1', y='sbp2', title='Linear Regression Plot')+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5, size=20, face='bold'))
